":[{"name":"Sully","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armelle, Christophe, Geralde, Luce, Pierre, Reynald.","English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from any of the three places called Sully in Calvados (Normandy), Aisne (Picardy), and Loiret (Centre); see 6 below.","English: of Norman origin, perhaps a habitational name from Sully (Glamorgan). However, the placename is manorial in origin, from the Norman surname in 1 above, which is recorded in Glamorgan in the 12th century."]}]},{"name":"Sara","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Sarah .  This is the form used in the Greek of the New Testament (Hebrews 11:11)."],"variants":[{"name":"Sarah","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the wife of Abraham and mother of Isaac. According to the Book of Genesis, she was originally called <i>Sarai</i> (possibly meaning ‘contentious’ in Hebrew), but had her name changed by God to the more auspicious <i>Sarah</i> ‘princess’ in token of a greater blessing (Genesis 17:15, ‘And God said unto Abraham, As for Sarai thy wife, thou shalt not call her name Sarai, but Sarah shall her name be’). This has been one of the most enduringly popular girls' names."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sara Sulley was born about 1176, in Llanmaes, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Walter De Sully, was 38 and her mother, Mabel De Torrington, was 24. She married William Malet III in 1215. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in Enmore Castle, Somerset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1176–":"umbes 1176–Surnud","1172–1242":"1172–1242","1176–Female":"1176–Surnud","1178–1256":"1178–1256","1206–1264":"1206–1264","1208–Female":"1208–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1140–1242":"1140–1242","1154–1235":"1154–1235","1154":"1154","1264":"1264","1176":"1176","1242":"1242","1140":"1140","1172":"1172","1206":"1206","about 1208":"umbes 1208","1215":"1